    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided S-1 filing text, here is the specific language and exact quotes regarding the timing, deployment, and forward-looking statements for V2 Mobile and Direct-to-Cell (satellite-to-mobile) services:\n\n### Timing of V2 Mobile Deployment\nThe filing explicitly targets 2027 for the deployment of the V2 Mobile satellites and outlines the prerequisites for launching commercial service:\n* **"We plan to expand our mobile constellation by deploying our next-generation mobile V2 Mobile satellites in 2027"**\n* **"we still require our V2 Mobile satellites to be in orbit and must complete the acquisition of the relevant spectrum from EchoStar before we can commence our planned commercial Gen2 service in the United States."**\n\n### Exact Quotes About V2 Mobile\nThe filing defines V2 Mobile satellites and outlines their intended capabilities and capacity improvements:\n* **“V2 Mobile satellites” refers to our next-generation mobile satellites, which are designed to provide more comprehensive satellite-to-mobile services, including broadband data and IoT connectivity and which we expect**\n* **"We plan to expand our mobile constellation by deploying our next-generation mobile V2 Mobile satellites in 2027 which, combined with the EchoStar spectrum acquisition and optimized 5G protocols, are expected to increase capacity by orders of magnitude compared to our first-generation constellation."**\n* **"In the United States, we expect to be able to provide 5G-like connectivity to a meaningful portion of existing unmodified devices through our Starlink Mobile Gen2 service utilizing our V2 Mobile satellites, either by operating on spectrum leased to us by MNO partners or by utilizing our own domestic spectrum holdings."**\n\n### Direct to Cell / Satellite-to-Mobile Architecture\nThe filing refers to "Direct to Cell" primarily as "satellite-to-mobile" or "mobile service," describing the technical architecture as follows:\n* **"We are extending the reach of Starlink beyond fixed and mobility terminals through our mobile service, connecting smartphones (with no modifications or incremental hardware) and other terrestrial devices directly to our satellites."**\n* **"Our mobile constellation builds on the same LEO architecture as our broadband network, with satellites specifically designed to communicate directly with everyday LTE handsets and IoT devices without requiring specialized or additional hardware."**\n* **"The expansion of our global satellite-to-mobile connectivity offerings depends substantially on our ability to enter into and maintain successful partnerships with telecommunications carriers and spectrum licensees globally..."**\n\n### Deployment Schedule & Launch Logistics\nThe filing details that V2 Mobile deployment relies on Starship, noting that current rockets cannot carry them:\n* **"anticipate that Starship will be able to deploy approximately 50 mobile satellites per launch, significantly increasing capacity per launch and accelerating the deployment of our next-generation constellation."**\n* **"Full reusability of Starship’s upper stage is not required to deploy our V3 satellites and V2 Mobile satellites in low-Earth orbit."**\n* **"Our current operational rockets, including Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy, are not capable of deploying V3 satellites and V2 Mobile satellites."**\n\n### Forward-Looking Statements About V2 Mobile\nThe filing includes several forward-looking statements and risk disclosures regarding V2 Mobile, relying on words like "expect" and "plan," and noting dependencies on Starship and regulatory approvals:\n* **"If we are unable to achieve the commercial development, anticipated performance, launch cadence, or cost efficiencies associated with Starship within expected timeframes, our ability to deploy next-generation V3 satellites, V2 Mobile satellites, and orbital AI compute infrastructure at scale... could be materially and adversely affected."**\n* **"We have an operational coordination agreement with EchoStar, which we expect to continue through 2026 and 2027, under which EchoStar has agreed to protect our lower-priority S-band V2 Mobile constellation."**\n* **"We are developing more comprehensive satellite-to-mobile services, which we refer to as our Starlink Mobile Gen2 services, including broadband data and IoT connectivity, which are expected to deliver resilient, infrastructure-independent connectivity worldwide..."**\n* **"achieving full 5G NR-NTN compliance and optimal performance would likely require handset manufacturers to implement hardware and software modifications... We do not have direct contractual arrangements with handset manufacturers; instead, we expect MNO partners, as major purchasers of mobile devices, to encourage or drive such adoption."**',
